<TITLE> DU students object to 'grade equivalencies' by employers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 18 (bdnews24.com)A group of Dhaka University students held protests on campus on Saturday against grade equivalence ratings announced by some companies for recruitment purposes. They demanded "rational equivalencies" for the ratings being used by some employers with regard to SSC and HSC examinations held between 2001-03, before the government had introduced the current grading guidelines. More than a hundred students, who passed their SSC examinations in those three years, joined the protests that including a human chain, a silent procession and mass signatures in support of their protest. They also handed a memorandum to DU vice chancellor Prof AAMS Arefin Siddique, urging authorities to help combat the "discriminatory ratings". The students said several public and private organisations, including the Public Service Commission, Dutch-Bangla Bank, Dhaka Bank, and Premier Bank equated GPA 4.5 with a first division pass, GPA 4.0-4.25 with second class and below GPA 4 with the third class division. The students claimed this was "discriminatory ". A large section of students will be victims of the grading inequality if the employers concerned attempt to use the equivalencies, they said. Over 80 per cent of students of the two batches (SSC and HSC) between 2001-03 would be regarded as third class passes according to the stated ratings, the students said
